    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"Forms-of-a-Linear-Function\"><h2>Forms-of-a-Linear-Function</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 2: Forms of Linear Equations</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Summarizes slope-intercept, standard, and point-slope forms of a linear function.</div>\n<p>There are three main forms of a linear function: slope-intercept form, standard form, and point-slope form.</p>\n<p><strong>Slope-Intercept form:</strong> $y=mx+b$. The slope is $m$, and the $y$-intercept is $(0,b)$.</p>\n<p><strong>Standard form:</strong> $ax+by=c$.</p>\n<p><strong>Point-Slope form:</strong> $y-k=m(x-h)$. The slope is $m$, and $(h,k)$ is a point on the line. For example, if the slope is $-7$ and the point $(20,-10)$ is on the line, the equation can be written $y-(-10)=-7(x-20)$ or $y+10=-7(x-20)$.</p>\n</section>",
